{
  "answer": "**The poem \"Sāre Jahān se Acchā Hindostān Hamārā\" (also known as *Tarana-e-Hindi*) is one of Allama Iqbal's most famous early patriotic works, composed around 1904 and first published in his 1905 collection *Baang-e-Dara* (or earlier journals).**\n\nHowever, it is not present in the Falsafa corpus. This corpus includes Iqbal's *Bang-e-Dara* (1924) split into three parts (100 chapters total), which contains other nationalist poems such as:\n\n- \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, ch. 26), praising India's historical and spiritual heritage with the refrain \"Mera watan wohi hai\" (\"That is my own homeland\").[^1]\n- \"Tarana-e-Milli\" (*Bang-e-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23), an anthem of Muslim universalism with the refrain \"Cheen o Arab hamara, Muslim hain hum, watan hai saara jahan hamara\" (\"From China to Arabia is ours; we are Muslims, the whole world is our homeland\").[^2]\n\nThese are thematically related but distinct from *Tarana-e-Hindi*. The exact poem you referenced, beginning \"Sāre jahān se acchā Hindostān hamārā / Hum bulbulen hain is kī, yeh gulistan hamārā,\" is from Iqbal's pre-*Bang-e-Dara* oeuvre and thus unavailable here.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 26 \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" (transliteration and translation variants available).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 \"Tarana-e-Milli\" (transliteration and translation variants available).",
